  "prompt": "Is the past tense of \"troubleshoot\" troubleshooted or troubleshot? Why?",
  "response": "The past tense of **\"troubleshoot\"** is **\"troubleshot\"**. This follows the pattern of irregular verbs where the past tense is formed by altering the vowel sound of the base verb, similar to how \"shoot\" becomes \"shot.\"\n\n### Why?\nThe verb \"troubleshoot\" is a compound of \"trouble\" and \"shoot.\" While \"shoot\" is an irregular verb with the past tense \"shot,\" \"troubleshoot\" inherits this irregularity. Thus, the past tense of \"shoot\" influences the past tense of \"troubleshoot,\" making it \"troubleshot.\"\n\n### Examples:\n- Present: \"I troubleshoot the issue.\"\n- Past: \"I troubleshot the issue.\"\n\n\"Troubleshooted\" is sometimes used informally, but it is not considered correct in standard English. Stick to \"troubleshot\" for formal or proper usage.",
